\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The GNS representation of a KMS state generates a 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Type III}_{1}$
\end_inset

 von Neumann factor (in relativistic QFT —
 Bisognano–Wichmann theorem) or 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Type II}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (in some non–relativistic cases).
 These are factors with no trace at all in the Type III case,
 or an unbounded trace in 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Type II}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 \SpecialChar allowbreak
.
 The non–sigma–finite measure is the shadow of the fact that you are in Type II or III territory,
 where the conventional density–matrix formulation is simply not available and KMS/modular theory takes over.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The Tomita-Takesaki modular theory is precisely the machinery that handles what "density matrix" would have done,
 without requiring one to exist.
 The modular operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 encodes the non–sigma–finite structure in a canonical operator–algebraic form.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

