\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
\emph on
Case 3:
 Failure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U}\left\Vert c_{m}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}<\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
This case has the most direct and elegant mapping to mixed states,
 via a precise integrability gap.
 The key identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \left|c_{m}\right\rangle \left\langle c_{m}\right|\right\Vert _{\mathrm{trace}}=\left\Vert c_{m}\right\Vert _{H}^{2}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
.
 The trace–class norm of a rank-1 projector goes as the square of the vector norm,
 not linearly.
 For finite measure spaces (including probability measures),
 Hölder's inequality forces 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mu\right)\subset L^{1}\left(\mu\right)$
\end_inset

,
 so the density–operator condition implies the vector condition.
 The two cases collapse together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
For infinite measure spaces,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mu\right)\not\subset L^{1}\left(\mu\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and the gap is real and generic.
 A concrete example:
 take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 = Lebesgue measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\left[1,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert c_{m}\right\Vert _{H}=m^{-3/4}$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{1}^{\infty}m^{-3/4}=\infty$
\end_inset

 (vector integral fails)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{1}^{\infty}m^{-3/2}=2<\infty$
\end_inset

 (density operator integral succeeds)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
After renormalizing so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}(\rho)=1$
\end_inset

,
 you obtain a perfectly well–defined mixed state,
 with no corresponding pure–state average wavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The physical interpretation is illuminating:
 the failure of 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U}\left\Vert c_{m}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}<\infty$
\end_inset


\series default
 means there is too much total coherent amplitude to form a pure superposition —
 the integral "wants to diverge" at the level of amplitudes.
 But 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U}\left\Vert c_{m}\right\Vert ^{2}<\infty$
\end_inset


\series default
 says the total intensity (probability weight) is finite,
 which is all that is needed for a statistical mixture.
 The mathematics is forcing you to describe the ensemble as a mixed state because no coherent pure–state description is available.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

