\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
Gelfand–Naimark–Segal,
 after Israel Gelfand,
 Mark Naimark,
 and Irving Segal.
 The GNS construction (early 1940s–1950s) shows that any positive linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{*}$
\end_inset

–algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 canonically defines a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\omega}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
,
 a representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\omega}:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}(H_{\omega})$
\end_inset

,
 and a cyclic vector |
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\omega}\rangle\in H_{\omega}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(A)=\langle\Omega_{\omega}|\pi_{\omega}(A)|\Omega_{\omega}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the fundamental theorem connecting the abstract algebraic formulation of quantum mechanics to the concrete Hilbert space formulation —
 the bridge between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(H)$
\end_inset

.
\emph default

